The FTIR spectra (Fig. 4
                        ) of CDs, TNs and 0.2CDs-TNs were carried out to study the bonding composition and functional groups of materials. All spectra display absorption peaks at 3427, 1630 and 1384cm−1, which are assigned to OH stretching vibration of adsorbed water, bending vibration of hydroxyl groups and skeletal vibration of symmetric carboxylate (CO) stretching, respectively [38,41]. Besides, the vibration peaks of NH (3220cm−1), COOH (1705cm−1), CN=(1441cm−1) can also be observed in CDs [42], signifying the presence of carboxylic and amide groups on the surface of CDs. Compared with TNs, 0.2CDs-TNs possess some new features. The CO peak becomes stronger and the peak of COC at 1257cm−1 
                        [43] is appeared, indicating the successfully coupling of CDs with TNs. What’s more, a new peak of CO at 1060cm−1 and a shift of the broad absorption band below 1000cm−1 can be observed, suggesting the formation of TiOC bonds in CDs-TNs composites [38,43,44].
